freeform.title: Understanding College Football Standings
freeform.custom_rich_text:
There are several key points to consider when understanding college football standings and college football power rankings.

College football standings are primarily based on teams' win-loss records against other teams in their conference. The team's performance in their respective conferences significantly impacts their position in the College Football Playoff picture. The more games a team wins, the higher the team will potentially be in the college football power rankings; conversely, more losses typically mean a lower standing in the college football power rankings.

The various columns in the college football standings represent a wealth of information about each team's performance. These include:

  • Wins: The count of games a team has won.

  • Losses: The count of games a team has lost.

  • Win Percentage: The ratio of wins to total games played, expressed as a decimal.

  • Points For: The total points a team has scored.

  • Points Against: The total points a team has conceded.

The college football standings are updated after each game, ensuring you always have the most recent information. With DraftKings Sportsbook, you'll stay informed about the current college football standings and your favorite team's path to the playoff all season long.

Factors Affecting College Football Standings

Numerous factors influence college football standings and college football power rankings. By understanding these, you can glean valuable insights into who will ultimately make the College Football Playoff. We'll examine the role of wins and losses, tiebreakers, and the significance of conference matchups in determining the college football standings.

With so few games in the college football regular season, a single loss can remove a team from contention in their conference and the College Football Playoff. Only the ACC, Big 12, Big Ten and SEC champions are guaranteed a spot in the College Football Playoff so any other team will need to have the best overall resume to make the playoffs.

The Sun Belt is the only conference with divisions where each divisional winner will make the conference championship game. In every other conference, the two teams with the best conference record will make the conference championship game. In the event of a tie at the top of the standings, tiebreakers such as head-to-head records, overall records and other factors will be used.

Conference matchups shape who will make the conference championship games and therefore, the College Football Playoff. It is important to track the conference standings throughout the season to know who has an edge to make the postseason. DraftKings Sportsbook provides extensive coverage of current college football standings and a variety of betting options to enrich your college football viewing experience.

freeform.title: Understanding NFL Standings
freeform.custom_rich_text:
To fully grasp NFL standings and NFL power rankings, there are several key points to consider. We'll unpack how these standings are determined, the meaning of the different columns, and their update frequency.

Current NFL standings are primarily based on teams' win-loss records throughout the regular season. The team's performance in their respective divisions and conferences significantly influences their position in the NFL standings. More victories mean a higher standing in NFL power rankings; conversely, more losses typically mean a lower standing in the NFL power rankings.

The various columns in the NFL standings represent a wealth of information about each team's performance. These include:

  • Wins: The count of games a team has won.
  • Losses: The count of games a team has lost.
  • Ties: The number of games that ended in a stalemate.
  • Win Percentage: The ratio of wins to total games played, expressed as a decimal.
  • Points For: The total points a team has scored.
  • Points Against: The total points a team has conceded.

The NFL standings are updated after each game, ensuring you always have the most recent information. With DraftKings Sportsbook, you'll stay informed about the current NFL standings and your favorite teams' performance throughout the season.

Factors Affecting NFL Standings

Numerous factors influence NFL standings, NFL power rankings and NFL playoff standings. By understanding these, you can glean valuable insights into team positioning and playoff prospects. We'll examine the role of wins and losses, tiebreakers, and the significance of divisional and conference matchups in determining football NFL standings.

Wins and losses form the basis of NFL standings, determining team positioning within divisions, conferences, and the overall league. More wins can boost a team's chances of making the playoffs, while losses can hinder progress, affecting both NFL power rankings and NFL playoff standings.

Tiebreakers come into effect when teams share a win-loss record. These rules, such as head-to-head record, divisional record, conference record, and strength of schedule, help determine team order within divisions, conferences, and NFL standings.

Divisional and conference matchups can greatly impact NFL standings and NFL playoff standings. Wins in these games can significantly boost a team's playoff chances. Understanding these factors helps fans and bettors to make informed decisions. DraftKings Sportsbook provides extensive coverage of current NFL standings and a variety of betting options to enrich your NFL experience.

freeform.title: About the March Madness Bracket
freeform.custom_rich_text:
The NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament March Madness bracket is released every March with 68 teams making the field to compete for a National Championship. Every Division 1 school that wins its conference championship game (pending certain rules) gets an automatic bid into the tournament, and the rest of the field is filled with at-large bids. Teams are seeded 1-16 in four different brackets throughout different regions of the country.

The first games that take place are the “First Four,” where we have four games between 11-seeds and 16-seeds to compete for the final four spots in the field. Once the field is down to 64 teams, the bracket is set, and you can begin to fill out your picks. The first round of the tournament always begins on a Thursday afternoon following Selection Sunday. Just prior to those Thursday tip-offs is generally when brackets lock.

Looking for Super Bowl prop bets? Check out our Super Bowl Prop Bets page and start placing bets on props including coin toss, Gatorade color, and more!*

*props available are dependent on the jurisdiction you are located in


Common Super Bowl Prop Bets

There might be only one game to bet on at the end of the football season, but by no means is there a shortage of potential plays for the Super Bowl. On top of the spread, game total or simply backing your team on the moneyline, there’s a litany of props available.

Player Props are the most common among the options you’ll find. These can range from game-long options like yardage props and touchdowns scored to very specific plays — the total yardage on a player’s longest rush, the total yardage on a player’s first reception or even which player will score the game’s first touchdown. Of course, bettors can also back who they believe will be named Super Bowl MVP.

But for those looking to broaden things, Team Props and Game Props are options. Instead of betting on the game total, bettors can simply back one team to go over or under their individual total for the Super Bowl. But, there are still ways to get in on even more specific outcomes, including some options bettors won’t see throughout the regular season — whether or not the opening kickoff will be a touchback, will any team successfully recover an onside kick and will there be a flea-flicker attempted being among the potential plays.

The Super Bowl Props don’t end there, though. Have a strong feeling about the Gatorade color that’ll be dumped on the winning coach’s head? There’s a prop for that. Do you believe “tails never fails” — or perhaps the opposite? There’s a prop bet for the opening coin toss. And be on the lookout for cross-sport bets, too!

By Geoff Ulrich | March 11th, 2021


The 2021 Masters is now only a month or so away. Yes, that last sentence is correct, a MONTH. It seems like only yesterday (four months actually) that Dustin Johnson was waxing the field to the tune of a five-shot win – a win which resulted in him breaking the all-time Masters scoring record and hitting 20-under par. The previous record was held by Jordan Spieth and Tiger Woods.


This year’s event will take place between April 8-11 and DraftKings Sportsbook already has odds up for the event. There will also be tons of great options for daily fantasy purposes on DraftKings too, but for now, let's focus on the odds and see where everyone’s at and who might be looking like a good futures target for some early investments.


The Favorites

Dustin Johnson remains the favorite as of writing at +550. It’s an incredibly small number, especially considering DJ was going off around +1000 pre-event when he won the Masters last fall. The outright favorites here don’t have a great record of coming through, though, and we haven’t seen a repeat winner here since Tiger Woods in 2001-2002.


Behind him, there’s a big group of players all bunched tightly together in the odds. Rory McIlroy and Justin Thomas both sit at +1000 while Jon Rahm sits just behind at +1100. All three men are still looking for their first green jacket and could conceivably challenge this year. All three have had ebbs and flows to start the year and all three are winless in 2021 as of the creation of this article — although Rory is in the mix at the API so that could change quickly.


Bryson DeChambeau and Brooks Koepka have also been bet down to very low numbers for this event and both sit at +1200. DeChambeau was the betting favorite at Augusta National in the fall and famously quipped that the course was playing like a par 67 for him — before finishing T34. Koepka’s odds have taken a huge turn lower after picking up a win at Phoenix in February. If you bet him in January or earlier for this event you’re sitting with some good value right now. Koepka’s finished T7 and T2 at this event over the past two seasons.


Betting Targets (DraftKings Sportsbook)

Patrick Cantlay +2500


Cantlay’s been on a serious roll of form over the past four to five months and it feels like he’s still not getting the proper respect in the betting odds. The American has moved up to No. 7 in the OWGR and has now finished T17 or better in each of his past six PGA TOUR starts. This year, he’s posted a third-place finish at Pebble Beach (where he led the field in SG: Tee to Green stats) and a second-place finish at the American Express, where he shot a brilliant 61 in the final round. The past five winners at Augusta have all posted at least one top-5 finish or better in the preceding three months leading up to the event and have also all been ranked inside the top 25 in the OWGR. Cantlay fits both those trends nicely. While I like the idea of taking both Cantlay and Xander Schauffele (+1800) in this range, Cantlay for me is the clear better value right now as there’s not much separating these two in form. This will be his fifth time playing Augusta and he’s finished T17 and T9 the past two seasons.


Paul Casey +4500


While Casey has often disappointed us in the big events, I can’t stop coming back to him in this range. The Englishman seems to be defying age as 2021 is setting up to be his best start to a competitive season in quite some time. Casey already picked up a win in January over in Dubai (Euro Tour) and also has two top 10s in two PGA TOUR starts as of the time of writing. Even his putting has looked improved in 2021, so if he can maintain his form with that club then he should have a real shot at grabbing his first major. Casey was a co-leader at Augusta after the first round last season (he opened with a 65) and has four top-15 finishes at Augusta over his past six trips there. In this range, there’s no one with a better mix of course history and current form for me to target.


Longshot (DraftKings Sportsbook)

Marc Leishman +10000


Leishman has been all over the map in terms of play over the past four to five months. He endured a terrible run of form last fall but righted himself with a T13 at Augusta in November. The top-15 finish represented his third top-15 finish at the event in his past seven tries. He’s been up near the lead on multiple occasions at Augusta and even held the 36-hole lead back at the 2018 Masters. The Aussie has shown better form with his irons in 2021, gaining 1.0 strokes or more on his approaches in four of his six PGA TOUR starts. We often see him go off at +6600 or lower in majors so his price really stands out, especially considering the decent start he’s had to 2021. If you’re looking for a player to invest in at bigger odds, he’s the best value on the board for me at +10000 or greater.


I am a promoter at DraftKings and am also an avid fan and user (my username is wavegoodbye) and may sometimes play on my personal account in the games that I offer advice on. Although I have expressed my personal view on the games and strategies above, they do not necessarily reflect the view(s) of DraftKings and I may also deploy different players and strategies than what I recommend above. I am not an employee of DraftKings and do not have access to any non-public information.

freeform.title: NFL Odds, Lines, Spreads, Moneylines, and the Growth of NFL Betting
freeform.custom_rich_text:
With the introduction of online betting, wagering on NFL games has only grown in popularity. Football betting with apps or on the web makes putting down stakes easier than ever, adding to the anticipation of watching your favorite team play.


Betting in the NFL Regular Season

The DraftKings Sportsbook app makes placing a bet on a football game super easy. The platform provides you with a virtual bet slip; you just add the games you want to place a wager on. Once you make a betting pick, the platform shows you all the types of bets you can make for your selections, the odds, and betting spreads for NFL games. Once you've made your picks and put down an amount to stake, a handy "Place Bets" button lets you finalize your wager.

With sports betting on NFL games, people typically bet on the results of upcoming games—namely, who will win and who will lose. But you can make wagers on outcomes beyond the winner and the loser, such as the number of total rushing yards or which team will get the most sacks. While we share the basics here, check out our guide on how to bet on football for a more in-depth explanation.


Types of Bets

When betting on NFL games, moneylines, totals (over/under), and spreads are the most popular methods for laying a wager on a football game.

Spread betting

A spread looks similar to this:

Team Spread Moneyline
New England -14.5 -120
Kansas City +14.5 +150

The negative number in the spread column shows the number of points the indicated team has to win for a wager to pay out. In this example, New England has to win by 15 points to win a bet placed on them. For the opposing team—in this case Kansas City—a bet on them pays out if they lose by fewer than 15 points or win the game. The decimal is there to ensure no push occurs on a bet. If the spread were to read -15/+15, a win by New England by fifteen points would force a betting tie, and the bookmaker would have to refund all bets.

The moneyline indicates the bet payout. In the case of New England, the negative number indicates how much you'd need to stake in order to win $100. The positive amount shows how much you'd win after placing a $100 bet on that team to win. If you were to bet on New England, you'd have to bet $120 to win $100. You'd also win back your initial $120 stake for a total of $220.

If you want to bet on Kansas City at +150, you'd need to put up a bet of $100. If they're victorious, you'd win $150. You'd also get back your initial $100 stake, for a total of $250, back into your pocket.

For smaller bets, the moneyline scales easily. You'd stake $12 on New England to win $10 and place $10 on KC to win $15.


NFL betting lines

NFL line betting—also called moneyline betting—simply takes the spread out of the picture. In this case, the bookmakers adjust the payout to account for the lack of point spread. A moneyline sheet might look similar to this:


Team Spread Moneyline
New England @ Kansas City New England -200/+200

The moneyline column works the same as with spread betting. In this case, you'd have to bet $200 to win $100 when betting on New England. The stake would be $100 to win $200 if you choose Kansas City to win.


Totals betting

Totals—or over/under—betting is probably the simplest way to place a wager. The oddsmaker puts up a total score, and you lay down the stakes as to whether the total number of points scored by both sides during the game will be more or less than the posted score.


Prop wagers

You aren't just limited to betting on the outcome of a game. There are numerous results you can lay down a wager on. NFL betting trends include prop wagers—also known as side bets. These side bets include who'll be the MVP of a particular matchup, how many points a specific player will score, which team will rush for the most yards, and a slew of other incidental wagers you can place to make the game even more exciting.


Live betting

Once the game has kicked off, you can place several bets in real time. Many bookmakers will allow you to bet on specific quarters, halves, or individual drives while the game progresses. Many side bets you can place before the game are available during game play, but the odds will shift continuously as the game progresses.

Keep in mind that once you lay down a live bet, you're locked into the odds as they were at the time of your wager. Increasing or decreasing odds won't affect the payout of a bet that you've already made.


Futures betting

Futures betting looks beyond the outcome of the most current game. Common futures bets include which two teams will make it to the Superbowl, the season's scoring stats for a player or a team, and even which team will win the championship game that year.

Once you place a futures wager, you're locked into the odds applicable when you made the bet. Percentages for betting on NFL games shift from week-to-week, as teams win or lose—increasing or reducing their odds throughout the season. The fluctuating numbers make futures betting interesting for anyone who's placed a bet, especially when you bet on a long shot at the beginning of the season and their performance throughout the year improves their chances of winning your bet.


History of the NFL

The NFL was established in Canton, Ohio in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association (AFPA). The organization changed its name to the National Football League in 1922. Today, we simply refer to it as the NFL. As a new organization—with only 18 teams at the time—the league underwent a period of adjustment and selected the annual champion based on the team that performed the best that year. It continued this way until the league adopted formal rules establishing annual championship games in 1933.

In 1950, the NFL absorbed its competitor league, the All-America Football Conference. They expanded further in 1960 when the NFL merged with the American Football League and expanded to 32 teams that year.

In 1960, the NFL dubbed the championship game "The Superbowl," and it became the most anticipated sporting event in the United States and the most watched annual event on television.

With football's rise in popularity, it stood to reason that betting would also become more prevalent. Sports betting outside of horseracing was illegal all across the U.S. until Nevada legalized gambling in 1931—with the strictest of regulations and a substantial gaming tax. In 1970, Congress reduced the gaming tax from 10% to 2%, and more states began to legalize sports betting. Congress passed the Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act in 1992 to prevent betting on sports, except in select states. The Supreme Court overturned the act in 2018, which allowed any state to legalize the practice that wished to do so.


Several vetted, legitimate online betting venues, such as DraftKings, operate within American legal guidelines and only offer the ability to wager within states where sports betting is legal.

faq.question: When does the NFL betting season start?
faq.answer: Bookmakers begin setting odds and opening betting for the upcoming season as soon as the NFL calendar is released. This is an ideal time to look at futures betting since you can place bets on any scheduled game. As the season progresses, odds for upcoming games will fluctuate, adding to the anticipation throughout weekly play.

faq.question: When is the NFL Draft?
faq.answer: The NFL draft is held over three days during the spring every year. Player selection always begins on a Thursday, and the final pick takes place that Saturday. The league only holds the first round on Thursday, which is the time coaches select the most promising players. The draft performs all subsequent selection rounds over the next two days.

faq.question: When are NFL Draft Odds available?
faq.answer: Draft odds become available as soon as the first player registers for the draft, and odds update for each new player who registers. As one player becomes the favorite, another player's odds will become longer. By the fall of the year preceding the draft, bookmakers have a number of names available to bet on, along with the chances of being selected in the first round. You can even place bets on which player will be selected first overall.

faq.question: Can bets be made during the preseason?
faq.answer: You can bet on preseason exhibition games just as easily as regular season games. Sportsbooks will post the odds a few weeks before the preseason game, and you can place moneyline bets, spread wagers, or totals just as you would a regular game.

faq.question: How many NFL teams are there?
faq.answer: The NFL is made up of 32 teams, split into two conferences—the AFC (American Football Conference) and the NFC (National Football Conference). Each conference splits into four divisions, which are divided by region—north, south, east, and west.

faq.question: How many teams make the NFL Playoffs?
faq.answer: Seven teams from each conference play single-elimination Playoff games. Games continue until each conference has one NFL Playoff champion who makes it to the Superbowl.

faq.question: What is the single biggest NFL betting event of the year?
faq.answer: The Super Bowl is hands-down the biggest NFL betting event of the year—every year. The Super Bowl determines the NFL grand champion of the year, and every member of each participating team receives a designer-crafted ring—unique to that year's competition—to signify their participation.

combinationEducationModal.descriptionParlay: A parlay is a single bet that links together two or more individual picks and is dependent on all of those picks winning. The benefit of placing a parlay is that the payout is higher than placing each individual bet separately.
combinationEducationModal.descriptionParlaySecond: For example, if you place a {0} parlay on the New England Patriots (-110) and the Seattle Seahawks (-120), your total payout would be {1} if both teams win (+250 parlay odds).
combinationEducationModal.descriptionTeaser: A teaser allows for the adjustment of point spreads and game totals on two or more picks. A fixed number of points are bought on all picks in the teaser. The number of picks selected and the number of points selected determine the payout odds.
combinationEducationModal.descriptionTeaserSecond: All picks must be successful in order for the bet to win. If a pick in the teaser is a push, that pick will be removed from the teaser and the odds will be adjusted accordingly. A push in a two pick teaser, without a loss, will be considered "no action" and the wager will be refunded. When placing a bet on a Super/Monster teaser, a push will result in a lost bet.

roundRobinsEducationModal.title: Round Robins
roundRobinsEducationModal.prefaceText: Round Robin bets enable you to place all combinations of the outcomes in your bet slip quickly and efficiently.
roundRobinsEducationModal.descriptionText:
Depending on the number of outcomes in your bet 
 slip, you can select from a number of Round Robin 
 options, which will actually place multiple parlay bets 
 on the various combinations available.
roundRobinsEducationModal.exampleText:
For example, if you have TOR Maple Leafs, LA Lakers, 
 and GB Packers all to win in your bet slip, by 
 selecting to place a 2 Pick Round Robin, you'd be 
 covering all combinations of those 3 outcomes (and 
 placing 3 bets in the one transaction).
roundRobinsEducationModal.combinationsExample:
The 2 Pick RR would be 
 TOR Maple Leafs + LA Lakers 
 TOR Maple Leafs + GB Packers 
 LA Lakers + GB Packers
roundRobinsEducationModal.payoutText:
In that instance, as long as 2 of the 3 teams win, you'll 
 receive a payout vs. a regular parlay where all 3 teams 
 would need to win.
roundRobinsEducationModal.supportText: For more information and detailed rules please go to

teaserEducationModal.title: Teaser Bet Type
teaserEducationModal.description: A teaser allows for the adjustment of point spreads and game totals on two or more picks. A fixed number of points are bought on all picks in the teaser. The number of picks selected and the number of points selected determine the payout odds.
teaserEducationModal.footballSpecial:
Super: 3 Pick 10-Point {0} (push loses) 
 Monster: 4 Pick 13-Point {1} (push loses)
teaserEducationModal.basketballSpecial:
Super: 3 Pick 8-Point {0} (push loses) 
 Monster: 4 Pick 10-Point {1} (push loses)
teaserEducationModal.rules: All picks must be successful in order for the bet to win. If a pick in the teaser is a push, that pick will be removed from the teaser and the odds will be adjusted accordingly. A push in a two pick teaser, without a loss, will be considered "no action" and the wager will be refunded. When placing a bet on a Super/Monster teaser, a push will result in a lost bet.

walletLearnMoreModal.title: What's in my balance?
walletLearnMoreModal.description: Your total balance is made up of your cash deposits, bonus and promotional funds. Each one works a little bit differently, so take a look below to learn more.
walletLearnMoreModal.cashBalanceDescription: This is cash you have available. If you've opted into any special bonuses, those bonuses might need to be completed or forfeited before you can withdraw the full amount.
walletLearnMoreModal.dkDollarsDescription: This is promotional currency that can be used anywhere on DraftKings. DK Dollars can't be withdrawn and must be used at least one time to make a wager or enter a contest. Anything you win is yours to keep! If you have DK Dollars in your account, DraftKings uses these to place wagers or enter contests first, before using your own cash.
walletLearnMoreModal.casinoBonusDescription: These are bonus funds that can only be used on DraftKings Casino. They are subject to play-through requirements as well as the terms and conditions of the bonus that you opted in to when you received these funds. These funds can not be withdrawn until the requirements of the bonus has been met. Your Casino Bonus can only be used in a jurisdiction where DraftKings Casino is offered.
